That makes so much sense — you’re wanting something more genuine, and it feels like you’re surrounded by people who only want to skim the surface. That disconnect can be exhausting, like you’re constantly editing yourself just to fit in. Wanting deeper conversations isn’t strange or “too much”; it’s a sign that you value meaning and emotional connection, and that’s a really healthy thing to want.

You might not be able to change how your current friends communicate, but there are ways to start finding or creating spaces where you can be that authentic version of yourself. Sometimes that looks like:
- finding one person — even outside your current circle — who seems curious or reflective, and trying a small, deeper conversation to see how they respond;  
- joining or building a group focused on something you care about (book clubs, volunteer work, creative projects), where meaning naturally comes up;  
- journaling or therapy to keep that side of you alive and clear, so you don’t depend solely on friends who may not “get it.”

Would you like me to help you think through what finding or building those connections might look like in your daily life?
